{"title_page": "Tim Waterstone", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Sir]] \n| name = Tim Waterstone\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1939|5|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland, UK\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = [[Tonbridge School]]\n| alma mater = [[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman, author\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = [[Rosie Alison]]\n| children = 8\n| parents = \n| relatives = \n}}\n'''Sir Tim Waterstone''' (born 30 May 1939) is a British businessman, author and philanthropist. He is the founder of [[Waterstones]], the United Kingdom-based [[bookseller|bookselling]] retail chain, the largest in Europe.\n\n==Early life==\nTim Waterstone was born on 30 May 1939 in [[Glasgow]], Scotland.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\">{{cite web|title=Timothy John Stuart WATERSTONE|url=http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/82840/Timothy-John-Stuart-WATERSTONE|website=[[Debrett's]]|accessdate=28 May 2016}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\">{{cite news|title=My Secret Life: Tim Waterstone, businessman and author, 71|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/my-secret-life-tim-waterstone-businessman-and-author-71-2100754.html|accessdate=27 May 2016|work=The Independent|date=8 October 2010}}</ref><ref name=Birth>{{cite web|title=Birthday's today|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/archive/2013-5-30.html |work=The Telegraph|accessdate=28 May 2014|date=30 May 2013|quote=Mr Tim Waterstone, bookseller, 74 }}</ref> He grew up in [[Crowborough]], East Sussex, England.<ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/> He was educated at [[Tonbridge School]] and [[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]], where he read English.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/><ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/>\n\n==Career==\nWaterstone worked for a broking firm in [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], India.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> Upon his return to England he worked as a marketing manager for [[Allied Breweries]], 1964\u201373 and then [[W.H. Smith]], 1973\u201381.<ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/>\n\nWaterstone founded the bookselling chain Waterstone's in 1982, after he took a \u00a36000 redundancy payment from W.H. Smith.  He set up his first store in Old Brompton Road, Kensington, west London; his personal model of literary bookselling proved successful and ten years later, in 1992, Waterstone's had grown to be the largest bookselling group in Europe.  <ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/><ref name=\"dailymail1\">{{cite news|author=John Stevens |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2085471/No-problems-grocers-Waterstones-gives-apostrophe-practical-anymore.html |title=No more problems for grocers: Waterstones gives up on its apostrophe because it's not practical anymore |work=Daily Mail |date= 12 January 2012|accessdate=12 January 2012 |location=London}}</ref> He became the founder chairman of [[HMV]] Media Group in 1998, which merged the businesses of Waterstone's and HMV.<ref name=\"guardiantimifreadingisgoing\"/> He left the group in 2001.<ref name=\"guardiantimifreadingisgoing\"/>\n\nWaterstone chaired the DTI Working Group on Smaller Quoted Companies and Private Investors in 1999.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> He was a founder investor in [[Bookberry]], a Moscow booksellers modelled on Waterstone's.<ref name=\"ftoligarchpoisedtobid\">{{cite news|last1=Barrett|first1=Claer|title=Oligarch poised to bid for Waterstone's|work=Financial Times|date=4 February 2011}}</ref> He became the chairman of Read Petite, an e-book company, in 2013.<ref name=\"guardiantimifreadingisgoing\"/>\n\nWaterstone has published four novels: ''Lilley & Chase'' (Hodder 1994), ''An Imperfect Marriage'' (Hodder 1995), ''A Passage of Lives'' (Hodder 1996) and ''In For A Penny In For A Pound'' (Atlantic 2010).<ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/> He has also published a semi-autobiographical business book, ''Swimming Against The Stream'' (Macmillan 2006) and many articles in the arts and business media. His memoir, ''The Face Pressed Against A Window'', was published by Atlantic Books in February 2019.\n\n==Philanthropy and political activity==\nWaterstone was a chairman or board member of English International (1987\u201392), the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]] (1990\u201397), Portman House Trust (1994\u201396), the [[Academy of Ancient Music]] (1990\u201395), Virago Press (1993\u201395), Jazz FM (1991\u20131993), the London International Festival of Theatre (1990\u201392), the Elgar Foundation (1992\u201398), the [[British Library]] (1995\u201397), [[King's College London]] Library (2000\u201302), [[Yale University Press]] (1992\u20132013), Chelsea Stores (1996\u20132007), FutureStart (1992\u20132009), [[Virago Press]] (1995\u20131996), [[Hill Samuel]] UK Emerging Companies Investment Trust plc (1996\u20132000) and Downing Classic VCT (1998\u20132003).<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/>\n\nHe has sat on the [[Booker Prize]] Management Committee, and acted as the Chairman of Judges for the Prince's Youth Business Trust Awards.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> He served as a member of the visiting committee of Cambridge University Library (2007\u20132013).<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> He chaired [[Shelter (charity)|Shelter]]'s 25th Anniversary Appeal.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> He served as Chancellor of [[Edinburgh Napier University]] (2007\u20132015).<ref name=\"ourhistorynapier\">{{cite web|title=Our history|url=http://www.napier.ac.uk/about-us/our-history|publisher=Edinburgh Napier University|accessdate=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nWaterstone supports the Labour Party (he chose Clement Attlee as his 'hero' in the initial 2001 BBC Radio 4 series Great Lives).<ref name=\"scotsmanbusinesstim\">{{cite news|title=Interview: Tim Waterstone, businessman|url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/interview-tim-waterstone-businessman-1-478170|accessdate=28 May 2016|work=The Scotsman|date=14 September 2010}}</ref> He was opposed to the [[Iraq War]] and took part in demonstrations against it.<ref name=\"scotsmanbusinesstim\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nWaterstone is twice divorced.<ref name=\"scotsmanbusinesstim\"/> He is married to the TV and film producer and novelist [[Rosie Alison]].<ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/> They have eight children, one of them being actress [[Daisy Waterstone]]. He resides in [[Holland Park]], London.<ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/><ref name=\"guardiantimifreadingisgoing\">{{cite news|last1=Harris|first1=John|title=Tim Waterstone: 'If reading is going be all digital in 50 years, so be it'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/apr/09/tim-waterstone-reading-entirely-digital|accessdate=28 May 2016|work=The Guardian|date=9 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nWaterstone is a member of the [[Garrick Club]].<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> He was knighted in the [[2018 Birthday Honours]] for services to bookselling and to charity.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.waterstones.co.uk/waterstonesweb/home.do Waterstones online]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[Edinburgh Napier University|Chancellor of Edinburgh Napier University]]\n  | years  = 2007\u2013present\n  | before = [[George Younger, 4th Viscount Younger of Leckie]]\n  | after = Incumbent\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waterstone, Tim}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:People from Crowborough]]\n[[Category:People educated at Tonbridge School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Catharine's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British Anglicans]]\n[[Category:People associated with Edinburgh Napier University]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Sir]] \n| name = Tim Waterstone\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1939|5|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland, UK\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = [[Tonbridge School]]\n| alma mater = [[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman, author\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = [[Rosie Alison]]\n| children = 8\n| parents = \n| relatives = \n}}\n'''Sir Tim Waterstone''' (born 30 May 1939) is a British businessman, author and philanthropist. He is the founder of [[Waterstones]], the United Kingdom-based [[bookseller|bookselling]] retail chain, the largest in Europe.\n\n==Early life==\nTim Waterstone was born on 30 May 1939 in [[Glasgow]], Scotland.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\">{{cite web|title=Timothy John Stuart WATERSTONE|url=http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/82840/Timothy-John-Stuart-WATERSTONE|website=[[Debrett's]]|accessdate=28 May 2016}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\">{{cite news|title=My Secret Life: Tim Waterstone, businessman and author, 71|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/my-secret-life-tim-waterstone-businessman-and-author-71-2100754.html|accessdate=27 May 2016|work=The Independent|date=8 October 2010}}</ref><ref name=Birth>{{cite web|title=Birthday's today|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/archive/2013-5-30.html |work=The Telegraph|accessdate=28 May 2014|date=30 May 2013|quote=Mr Tim Waterstone, bookseller, 74 }}</ref> He grew up in [[Crowborough]], East Sussex, England.<ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/> He was educated at [[Tonbridge School]] and [[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]], where he read English.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/><ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/>\n\n==Career==\nWaterstone worked for a broking firm in [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], India.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> Upon his return to England he worked as a marketing manager for [[Allied Breweries]], 1964\u201373 and then [[W.H. Smith]], 1973\u201381.<ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/>\n\nWaterstone founded the bookselling chain Waterstone's in 1982, after he took a \u00a36000 redundancy payment from W.H. Smith.  He set up his first store in Old Brompton Road, Kensington, west London; his personal model of literary bookselling proved successful and ten years later, in 1992, Waterstone's had grown to be the largest bookselling group in Europe.  <ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/><ref name=\"dailymail1\">{{cite news|author=John Stevens |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2085471/No-problems-grocers-Waterstones-gives-apostrophe-practical-anymore.html |title=No more problems for grocers: Waterstones gives up on its apostrophe because it's not practical anymore |work=Daily Mail |date= 12 January 2012|accessdate=12 January 2012 |location=London}}</ref> He became the founder chairman of [[HMV]] Media Group in 1998, which merged the businesses of Waterstone's and HMV.<ref name=\"guardiantimifreadingisgoing\"/> He left the group in 2001.<ref name=\"guardiantimifreadingisgoing\"/>\n\nWaterstone chaired the DTI Working Group on Smaller Quoted Companies and Private Investors in 1999.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> He was a founder investor in [[Bookberry]], a Moscow booksellers modelled on Waterstone's.<ref name=\"ftoligarchpoisedtobid\">{{cite news|last1=Barrett|first1=Claer|title=Oligarch poised to bid for Waterstone's|work=Financial Times|date=4 February 2011}}</ref> He became the chairman of Read Petite, an e-book company, in 2013.<ref name=\"guardiantimifreadingisgoing\"/>\n\nWaterstone has published four novels: ''Lilley & Chase'' (Hodder 1994), ''An Imperfect Marriage'' (Hodder 1995), ''A Passage of Lives'' (Hodder 1996) and ''In For A Penny In For A Pound'' (Atlantic 2010).<ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/> He has also published a semi-autobiographical business book, ''Swimming Against The Stream'' (Macmillan 2006) and many articles in the arts and business media. His memoir, ''The Face Pressed Against A Window'', was published by Atlantic Books in February 2019.\n\n==Philanthropy and political activity==\nWaterstone was a chairman or board member of English International (1987\u201392), the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]] (1990\u201397), Portman House Trust (1994\u201396), the [[Academy of Ancient Music]] (1990\u201395), Virago Press (1993\u201395), Jazz FM (1991\u20131993), the London International Festival of Theatre (1990\u201392), the Elgar Foundation (1992\u201398), the [[British Library]] (1995\u201397), [[King's College London]] Library (2000\u201302), [[Yale University Press]] (1992\u20132013), Chelsea Stores (1996\u20132007), FutureStart (1992\u20132009), [[Virago Press]] (1995\u20131996), [[Hill Samuel]] UK Emerging Companies Investment Trust plc (1996\u20132000) and Downing Classic VCT (1998\u20132003).<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/>\n\nHe has sat on the [[Booker Prize]] Management Committee, and acted as the Chairman of Judges for the Prince's Youth Business Trust Awards.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> He served as a member of the visiting committee of Cambridge University Library (2007\u20132013).<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> He chaired [[Shelter (charity)|Shelter]]'s 25th Anniversary Appeal.<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> He served as Chancellor of [[Edinburgh Napier University]] (2007\u20132015).<ref name=\"ourhistorynapier\">{{cite web|title=Our history|url=http://www.napier.ac.uk/about-us/our-history|publisher=Edinburgh Napier University|accessdate=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nWaterstone supports the Labour Party (he chose Clement Attlee as his 'hero' in the initial 2001 BBC Radio 4 series Great Lives).<ref name=\"scotsmanbusinesstim\">{{cite news|title=Interview: Tim Waterstone, businessman|url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/interview-tim-waterstone-businessman-1-478170|accessdate=28 May 2016|work=The Scotsman|date=14 September 2010}}</ref> He was opposed to the [[Iraq War]] and took part in demonstrations against it.<ref name=\"scotsmanbusinesstim\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nWaterstone is twice divorced.<ref name=\"scotsmanbusinesstim\"/> He is married to the TV and film producer and novelist [[Rosie Alison]].<ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/> They have eight children, one of them being actress [[Daisy Waterstone]]. He resides in [[Holland Park]], London.<ref name=\"independentmysecretlife\"/><ref name=\"guardiantimifreadingisgoing\">{{cite news|last1=Harris|first1=John|title=Tim Waterstone: 'If reading is going be all digital in 50 years, so be it'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/apr/09/tim-waterstone-reading-entirely-digital|accessdate=28 May 2016|work=The Guardian|date=9 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nWaterstone is a member of the [[Garrick Club]].<ref name=\"debrettstimothyjohnstuart\"/> He was knighted in the [[2018 Birthday Honours]] for services to bookselling and to charity.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.waterstones.co.uk/waterstonesweb/home.do Waterstones online]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[Edinburgh Napier University|Chancellor of Edinburgh Napier University]]\n  | years  = 2007\u